### if let in Rust

`if let` provides a concise way to match a single pattern without the boilerplate of a full `match` expression.

---

### if let vs match

```rust
// Verbose match
let optional = Some(7);
match optional {
    Some(x) => println!("Value: {}", x),
    None => {},
}

// Concise if let
if let Some(x) = optional {
    println!("Value: {}", x);
}

// if let with else
if let Some(x) = optional {
    println!("Value: {}", x);
} else {
    println!("No value");
}
```

---

### Common Use Cases

| Use Case | Example |
|----------|---------|
| Option unwrapping | `if let Some(val) = option { }` |
| Result checking | `if let Ok(val) = result { }` |
| Enum variant check | `if let Status::Active = status { }` |

> **Key Point:** Use `if let` when you care about matching one specific pattern and want to ignore the rest. Use `match` when you need exhaustive handling of all patterns.

codeExample:
fn main() {
    let config_max = Some(3u8);

    if let Some(max) = config_max {
        println!("Maximum is configured to {}", max);
    } else {
        println!("No maximum configured");
    }

    // Equivalent match is more verbose:
    // match config_max {
    //     Some(max) => println!("Maximum is {}", max),
    //     None => {},
    // }
}
